\begin_layout Subsection
Double Ciphers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Idea:

\series default
 Double-encryption.
 Instead of using a single key,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 use two keys,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/itciph.emf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hope:

\series default
 Complexity of exhaustive attack grow from
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{2^{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the original key-length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
If an encryption is closed under composition then iterating it for any number of times is pointless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
That is,
 if for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2}$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{3}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\enc_{k_{2}}\left(\enc_{k_{1}}\left(x\right)\right)=\enc_{k_{3}}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 then we could just exhaustively search for such 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
then we could just exhaustively search for such k3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ideal Ciphers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/itciph.emf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
ideal cipher model
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\str n$
\end_inset

 sample a random permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\enc_{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\str n$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\dec_{k}$
\end_inset

 denote its inverse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $\enc_{k},\dec_{k}$
\end_inset

 for any given key 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a unit-cost operation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The attack model:
 
\emph default
A pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k_{1},k_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 of random keys is sampled uniformly.
 Our goal is to recover the keys given oracle access to the encryption scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Meet in the Middle Attack
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/meetinthemiddle.emf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Goal:
 
\series default
Recover the two keys 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Ask for a pair of plaintext/ciphertext 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 for the new scheme,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\enc_{k_{2}}\circ\enc_{k_{1}}\right)\left(x\right)=y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find all candidates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k,k'\right)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\enc_{k}\left(x\right)=\dec_{k'}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How many such pairs exist?
 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 in expectation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Use another plaintext/ciphertext pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x',y'\right)$
\end_inset

 to filter out inconsistent candidates.
 Whp,
 only the right key survives.
 (If not,
 use another pair).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Algorithm
For each key 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 store 
\begin_inset Formula $\enc_{k}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in list 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 and store 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 sort lists in time 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 and find intersection in time 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Meet in the Middle Attack:
 Performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Time:
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\series bold
Space:
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare this to exhaustive search over the space of a
\emph on
 single
\emph default
 key:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Time:
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 
\series bold
Space:
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $O\left(1\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Conclusion
Double cipher (two iterations) does not add much to security (though it adds some,
 esp.
 if fast memory is expensive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Triple Cipher
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/tcip1.emf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/tcip2.emf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first version utilizes three independent keys 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2},k_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The second,
 just two - 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Quotes qld
\end_inset

middle box
\begin_inset Quotes qrd
\end_inset

 employs decryption rather than encryption.
 This results in backward compatibility:
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1},k_{2},k_{3}=k$
\end_inset

,
 this is identical to a single encryption using 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the key is unknown,
 decryption (should) also be a pseudorandom function,
 so using 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k_{2}}$
\end_inset

 does not reduce security.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Both versions are susceptible to a meet in the middle attack,
 albeit one that uses a list of size 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2n}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is length of keys).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This is the best attack known for version (1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For version (2),
 there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 attack using 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(2^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 chosen input/output pairs.
 This substantially reduces the practical risk of such attack.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Conclusion
Security is a subtle issue - Best to have a proof of security.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

